[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating JDK path issues**\n\nI’m thinking about the repo instruction to \"assume JAVA_HOME JDK21,\" which feels outdated. I wonder if the forge workflow has access to `/usr/lib/jvm`, but tests shouldn’t depend on that local path. Maybe I could look for a candidate JDK using environment variables or SDKMAN in the test? Though, that seems like it might violate the version-agnostic approach I’m aiming for. It’s a bit tricky!\n\n**Configuring build arguments**\n\nI think I need to add `tasks.named(\"nativeTestCompile\") { buildArgs.add(\"-Djava.security.manager=allow\") }` and configure the test JVM. It might be a good starting point, but I’m noticing that JDK 25 isn’t really working right now. There’s also the issue where it looks like forge coverage didn’t pick up on the native runtime arguments because I haven't added the build arguments. It seems I’ll need to include both build and runtime options to resolve this.\n\n**Evaluating test startup**\n\nI'm considering the global initial SM in all tests and wondering if the class might not be found at VM startup before the test classes load from the classpath. I know it is on the classpath, and for native image startup, the test class is included. However, it seems I might need to look into escaping issues. There’s something here that doesn’t quite add up, so I need to dig deeper.\n\n**Planning code adjustments**\n\nI'm looking at making a patch for the custom initial state machine, and I think I should rename the method too, maybe to something clearer? It's always good to keep things well-structured and intuitive. It might help others (or even future me) understand the code better. So, I’ll consider what name would best reflect its functionality. Let’s explore a few options for names and get this patch in place!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_04065ac85cb3361e0169fc30a5a760819ca25f0f532e6f0d55\",\"type\":\